Bothwell Middle School
September 8 at 4:27 PM ·

Dear Families,
Day 1 was a success! Thank you for all of your support, patience, and grace as we establish the new year given the circumstances.

Reminder for drop off/pick up: Please use the loops in the FRONT of the building. Please do not go to the back of BMS as this is staff parking and the loop that the busses use. We cannot have traffic in the bus loop at the beginning or end of the day. We apologize if our video was confusing. Thanks for understanding!
We look forward to another great day tomorrow. New routines take practice for all of us! Thanks for working so well with us.

Bothwell Middle School
September 4 at 8:35 PM ·

Bothwell Families,

We decided to create two different videos to help our students and families have better insight on the upcoming school year. Though we understand that most of our 7th and 8th graders know the layout of our building, we felt obligated to develop a virtual orientation for our incoming sixth-graders as well as those new to the district.

Furthermore, due to COVID-19, we created new procedures for lunch and recess. Our lunch/recess video tour will help our students understand those new procedures.

Please click below to view our videos.

Enjoy!

Welcome to Bothwell video Tour:
https://youtu.be/uq-t0bRNf_8

Recess/Lunch Tour
https://youtu.be/tSkjvUsufSA

post_text:
MAPS received some great news Tuesday morning. Our food service program is able to function under new guidelines allowing all students to receive free breakfast and lunch through December 31st of this year or until funding runs out. No need to deposit funds for meals for the foreseeable future!!!

Just a reminder, we still receive other sources of funding based on our percentage of free and reduced eligible applications. Please, please fill out these confidential forms so MAPS can receive vital funds for At Risk students, Title services and other programs. We hope all students take advantage of this opportunity.

post_text:
2020-21 MAPS School Bus Routes

Complete information regarding the 2020-21 MAPS bus routes is available as a download on the MAPS website. https://www.mapsnet.org/common/pages/DisplayFile.aspx?itemId=12339788
Please check this information carefully. If you advised the Transportation Department that you need busing and don’t see a stop that works for you, or if you have any other busing related questions, please contact the Transportation Department at 225-5774 or 225-5773.
If transportation arrangements change, parents and guardians should complete a new Transportation Request form. You can find the Google Form on the MAPS website at: https://www.mapsnet.org/district_departments/transportation. Please be aware that it may take some time to accommodate changes in busing because there will be assigned seating.
MAPS will be requiring all students to wear masks on the bus. If you have any questions regarding transportation, please call 225-5774.

MESSAGE FROM SUPERIOR HILLS ELEMENTARY SCHOOL PRINCIPAL SEDGWICK

Good afternoon Superior Hills Families,

I'd like to share two resources/links with you which I’m hoping will help you better understand our back-to-school plans for this coming school year. First, I'm happy to share a virtual town hall we're using as part of our open house this year. I'm so grateful for the help of our students, staff and parents for this pre-recorded video and hope you find it informative. The second resource, which is referenced multiple times in the town hall, is a website highlighting some of the more pertinent points of our back to school planning. Both resources can be found below:

Virtual Town Hall:
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1EDcp1DLfLFLw3r3kezoLIZOnIbOR77ss/view?usp=sharing

Superior Hills Back To School Site: https://sites.google.com/mapsnet.org/sh-remote-learning-platform/home

Viewing these resources may leave some of you with additional questions. As always, please feel free to call or write if you need additional information.

Be well and see you soon!

post_text: Thank you Community Foundation of Marquette County!
shared_text:
Community Foundation of Marquette County
July 21 at 3:33 PM ·

We were proud to award $10,000 to support the Education Foundation for Marquette Public Schools 1st to Finish Childhood Savings Account Fund! This grant is awarded from the unrestricted, endowed Fund for Marquette and will support savings accounts for first graders in Marquette Area Public Schools.

Children’s Savings Accounts (CSAs) are long-term savings accounts that help all children and their families build savings for the future. To help accounts grow, account holders receive incentives such as initial deposits and savings matches from third parties. Family, friends and the children themselves also make contributions. The “1st to Finish” program will open a savings account in the name of each participating first grader. Funds can be used for any qualifying career or educational expenses after high school.

IMAGE CAPTION: Representatives from the Community Foundation of Marquette County present a check to representatives from the Education Foundation for Marquette Public Schools to support the 1st to Finish CSA Fund.

post_text:
2020 School Board Election Dates and Deadlines

School Board elections take place on even-year November general election dates. Candidates who plan to run for their local school board at the November 2020 election must file an Affidavit of Identity and either a nonpartisan nominating petition or a nonrefundable fee with the Marquette County Clerk’s Office by 4:00 p.m. on Tuesday, July 21, 2020. Failure to file an Affidavit of Identity and the petition or fee by this deadline will bar the candidate from appearing on the ballot.

Marquette Area Public Schools will have two open six year seats.

For more information or to obtain the Affidavit of Identity or petition, please contact the Marquette County Clerk’s Office at 906-225-8330.

post_text:
2020 School Board Election Dates and Deadlines

School Board elections take place on even-year November general election dates. Candidates who plan to run for their local school board at the November 2020 election must file an Affidavit of Identity and either a nonpartisan nominating petition or a nonrefundable fee with the Marquette County Clerk’s Office by 4:00 p.m. on Tuesday, July 21, 2020. Failure to file an Affidavit of Identity and the petition or fee by this deadline will bar the candidate from appearing on the ballot.

Marquette Area Public Schools will have two open six year seats.

For more information or to obtain the Affidavit of Identity or petition, please contact the Marquette County Clerk’s Office at 906-225-8330.

BMS Yearbook is teaming with Jostens to offer all students free access to a digital yearbook signing program.

Jostens Yearbook Digital Signing Pages gives BMS students the chance to create virtual signing pages, invite their friends to leave messages, and print out the final pages to keep with the yearbook as a permanent keepsake. This is free to every student whether they purchased a yearbook or not.

Here is the link they use to access the program:

*Yearbooks will be handed out in the Fall. Information will be sent out when the time nears.

**Students your school email will not allow you to receive the confirmation email. You will need to use a personal email address.

As always remember to be kind and courteous, these are keepsakes!

Avenue.

post_text: JJ Packs will be wrapping up for the school year next week, but will be back at it in the fall when school commences. A huge "THANK YOU" to JJ Packs, a nonprofit volunteer-based organization in Marquette, for all of your hard work to provide food for our kids in need! Thanks to the volunteers for your dedication and to all of the donors for your support in providing supplemental nutrition for our families! You are appreciated!

¨The Art classroom has always been a place of experimentation, resourcefulness, and adaptability. This exhibit aims to represent these qualities that are so present in our students. We could not have the end of the year Art exhibit that we planned on, so we adapted and have this impressive virtual collection to share. I am honored to work with these creative individuals. Please spend some time with the creative, technical, and impressive work that our Bothwell students have created.¨ -Mr.Pawlowski (BMS Art Teacher)

Marquette Alternative High School
May 20 at 1:49 PM ·

MAHS would like to congratulate our Local scholarship recipients and Kaufman Award winner.

Ava Gillespie- Kaufman Award
Kya Beltran - Local Scholarship
Emily Hage- Local Scholarship
Taylor Peterson - Local Scholarship

As principal of Marquette Alternative High School I very much want to thank Marquette Area Public Schools Education Foundation for their continued dedication to students. I would also like to thank the Kaufman family for their endless work to better the future of our students.

I am not in the shared video but enjoyed zooming with our winners and I hope they know they have forever changed all of our lives for the better.

Also, thank you to my faculty and support staff for never wavering and never ceasing to offer love to our kiddos.

Andrew Crunkleton￼￼￼

Thank you to Marquette Senior High School Teacher Eric Hammerstrom for producing this amazing tribute to the MSHS Class of 2020!

Message from Mr. Hammerstrom:
"Here's to You" was written by an Indiana High School Senior named Abby Bannon, whose mom shared a Facebook video of Abby performing a song she wrote. I saw her mom's post, and asked if I could use the song to produce a tribute to the Marquette Senior High School class of 2020.

Thank you, Abby, for granting permission. Here's to you, too.
--Mr. H

post_text:
Teacher Appreciation Week 2020

This week is National Teacher Appreciation Week!

Our wonderful teachers at Marquette Area Public Schools are examples of the heart of this profession. Every day they affect positive change in the lives of our young people and we are so very fortunate to have them as teachers in our district.

Although schools are closed and not providing in-person instruction, our teachers are providing our students with continued learning so that every student has the tools they need to reach their full potential. Their leadership and influence has made such a positive difference!

THANK YOU teachers for realizing your amazing gifts and sharing them with our students!!

THANK YOU teachers for realizing your amazing gifts and sharing them with our students!!

post_text: Wow! 4,151 3D Printed Face Shields Made in 30 Days! Thank you MAPS Teacher Becky LaBrecque and Makers United!
shared_text:
Becky LaBrecque is with Kevin Bell and 19 others.
April 22 at 10:27 AM ·

One month ago today I had an idea.💡

I discovered a need that felt too big to fill alone.

1000 3D printed face shields were needed!
I knew my colleagues would help. And I have network marketing skills😎. So I went to work!

I had no idea it would grow into this.
The network grew so quickly. Makers from all over the region rallied. Word spread. People I never met before joined in and went full throttle towards our goal.

More organizations and businesses reached out for our help. 🙏
And even more stepped up to donate and support our work.💪

As of today this crew has turned in 4,151 3D printed face shields which were distributed all over the Upper Peninsula. And this graphic doesn't even show all the efforts around the U.P.! This is just the little effort that I sparked with a little social media magic. ❤️🙏
#thankful #UPStrong #MichiganStrong #WeAreMakers #YooperMakersUnited #3Dprintedfaceshields #3DprintedPPE #SeeWhatNetworkMarketingCanDo #BeTheLight #HelpOthers #SupportYourCommunity

I tagged a few of the makers here. If I missed you, please tag yourself!

post_text:
On behalf of the Marquette Area Public Schools Board of Education we sincerely appreciate the public’s participation in our recent survey used to gather input on our high school nickname.

Consumer Connections out of Green Bay, WI, conducted the survey with the following facts and results:
* 21,241 surveys mailed out to district registered voters
* 4,799 valid votes received
* 1,607 cards returned undeliverable by USPS due to address
changes
* Voting options were randomized
* 59.012% supported keeping current nicknames
* 40.988% supported seeking a new nickname

MAPS Board of Education and administration is currently focused solely on meeting the needs of our students and community in dealing with COVID-19. The Board will address the results of the survey, as well as a vote bringing closure to the nickname debate, at a later time more appropriate to addressing this matter. This will be scheduled with adequate notice and conducive to full public participation.

Frequently Asked Questions - School Closure COVID-19

Marquette Senior High School
April 2 at 2:04 PM ·

Governor Whitmer announced today that all K-12 schools in Michigan will close for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. While there are many questions that remain, I would like to answer a few initial questions.

1) As required by the executive order, MSHS is developing a "Continuity of Learning & COVID-19 Response Plan" to ensure learning continues for all MSHS students during the closure. Details will be shared once the plan has been finalized.

2) Seniors, on track for graduation, will graduate this year. Details are being worked out for both seniors and underclassmen to advance. (Students will not have to make up the school year)

3) More information is available on our School Closure COVID-19 FAQ page at https://docs.google.com/document/d/1J_3FwCpu8V3nvDlNtNyPez50rOVS_kRQsr1_p1zdfpI/edit?usp=sharing

We will continue to update this document as more information becomes available.

Students - Remember to check your student email regularly.

Wishing you all good health,
Jon Young, Principal, MSHS

post_text:
2020-2021 Kindergarten Registration

If your child will be five years old on or before December 1, 2020, and you missed registering for Kindergarten or Junior Kindergarten (this age requirement is mandatory for both kindergarten and junior kindergarten) for the 2020-2021 school year, you can email us at mapsinfo@mapsnet.org and we will mail a registration packet to you so you can start filling it out. You will still need to bring us an original birth certificate (state law requires that we see and make a copy of the student’s original birth certificate), immunization record, and proof of residency (i.e., utility bill or driver’s license) once the offices open up again. This email contact from you will help us to plan for your child and will enable us to contact you once the offices are open.

Since our offices are closed due to the "Stay Home, Stay Safe" executive order, it may take some time for the packet to arrive. However, we will get it to you as soon as possible. Thanks for your patience and help.

We are looking forward to welcoming the Class of 2033 to MAPS!

shared_text:
Jenna Smith - Marquette City Commission
March 31 at 4:45 PM ·

#MarquetteMoment Proclamation.

WHEREAS, the citizens of City of Marquette, along with the rest of Michigan, are facing an extraordinary time of disruption to their daily lives and routines due to the COVID 19 outbreak and the “Stay Home, Stay Safe” Executive Order (EO 2020-21) and;

WHEREAS, in addition to physical health, the mental and emotional wellbeing of Marquette is of paramount importance to the City Commission and the community and; .

WHEREAS, the Mayor and City Commission feel it is important that the City provide an outlet where residents and families can provide comfort and safely interact with each other; .

NOW, THEREFORE, I, Jenna Smith, Mayor of Marquette, do hereby proclaim the start of the “Marquette Moment” community initiative where every evening at 6:30 p.m. residents and families are encouraged to come out of their homes, wave to neighbors, visually check in with each other, and generally provide comfort and safely interact with each other within the guidelines of proper social distancing. .

DATED this 30th day of March, 2020.
Jenna Smith, Mayor

shared_text:
WEVIDEO.COM
At Bothwell We...(pt. 3)v2

Bothwell Middle School
March 22 at 8:35 PM ·

Mr. Pawlowski's 6th-grade sections have been creating an ongoing project throughout the 2019-20 school year. But, because the fourth quarter section of 6th graders has yet to participate in this project, it's not quite finished. However, we thought it would be a great time to share the in-progress results with you during this unprecedented time.

A little about the project - students were asked to make quick (5-10 seconds) clips to complete the statement "At Bothwell We ______." The results have been a combination of creative ideas of making words, collaborating with friends, stop-motion experiments, and more. Again, the project is not finished and we hope to add more to the video. I believe Mr. Pawloski stated it perfectly when he said, "Although it's not finished, I think it still does a lot to remind us that Bothwell is more than a physical place, it is a community that stretches beyond the building walls."

Enjoy!

post_text: A Huge "THANK YOU" to JJPacks, a nonprofit volunteer-based organization in Marquette, for all of your hard work to provide food to our kids in need! Please see their post below on how you can donate on-line.
shared_text:
JJ Packs
March 16 at 8:16 PM ·

We have had many people reach out to us wondering about how to donate to JJPacks. The outpouring of care and concern in our community is wonderful. We do indeed have neighbors who are in need at this time. Any donation amount will go directly into buying food for kids in need. Let's feed our kids while we flatten the curve!

Here's how you can donate:
We are excited to announce a link for on-line donations.

https://marquette.revtrak.net/jjpacks/

Gift cards for JJPacks can also be purchased at Super One and Econo Foods at their service counters. Both stores will keep the cards for us, and we will then use them when ordering for our packs.

March 16 at 3:48 PM ·

We have had several inquiries today asking if we were still holding shows or would be open to private gatherings. The answer to that is no.

We follow Marquette Area Public Schools closures. The Shiras Planetarium is closed until further notice. We will open when the schools open again. We will address our updated programming schedule at that time.

All tickets purchased on our website for a cancelled event were refunded last week Thursday.

Thank you for your understanding and support! Stay well in this difficult time.

Marquette Area Public Schools announces School of Choice openings for non-residents in grades K-12 for the 1st semester of the 2020-2021 school year. Application forms may be obtained at any MAPS school building, at the Superintendent's office, or downloaded from the MAPS website. Completed application forms will be accepted through Friday, September 11, 2020. The district will make every effort to accommodate building preference at the elementary level, but retains the right to make the final building selection for student placement. The enrollment deadline for students accepted under the School of Choice program is Friday, September 11, 2020.

Students must reside within the Marquette-Alger RESA to be eligible for School of Choice at MAPS.

post_text:
Spread Goodness Day meets March is Reading Month!

One hundred and seventy (170) Marquette Senior High School students will be reading books aloud to elementary classes at Superior Hills, Sandy Knoll, and Cherry Creek to spread goodness and promote "March is Reading Month" on Friday, March 13. To celebrate, there will also be an assembly at Sandy Knoll with Anna Dravland - founder of Spread Goodness Day - in which MSHS students help pass out sunglasses with Anna to all of the elementary students to promote this year's theme, "Making the future so bright, you're going to need shades."
